```

The function captures the current parser state, then parses the parameters and body of the definition. It pushes either a Mixin or Function scope onto the stack before parsing the block, then pops it back off and returns a new Definition object with all the collected information.

Now I'm thinking about whether there could be memory leaks on error paths. Since libsass uses reference-counted smart pointers for these `_Obj` types, the allocations are automatically managed—if an exception occurs during parsing, the smart pointers will clean up any partially constructed objects.

